content.description: Starts somewhat in the white limestone but quickly moves to the right. Execute an extremely powerful boulder problem on sharp rock which doesn't let up until you're standing above the bulge. Clip the anchors.
content.location: Bring a stick clip if there's no bail biner on #2. Aiding from #2 to the chains is 5.12+ effort by itself.

content.description: Start on the rock mound left of Snaggletufaed. Move up and left to gain a jug, then bear down on terrible crimps and contort into an extremely high heel moving through a tough boulder problem. Move up and left, finishing on the anchors for "Out of the Shadow"
content.location: Scramble up the rock mound from left via the small approach trail. Watch for Poison Ivy.

content.description: After Bolt 2 you are tempted to skip Bolt 3, since it jigs right and the anchors are so close by.  Don't skip it.  Move right to Bolt 3 and then far up to the mini-roof with the hole in it, at the clifftop.  Then reach left to clip the anchors.  This dogleg path milks some fun technical moves.
content.location: To the right of Friends and Lovers and Zoey's wall.

content.description: 2.5' from Snuff the Rooster but the anchors are higher and invisible.  The route uses (right-handed) three holds on Snuff.  Left hand holds are all left of the boltline and work increasingly away from it, onto the arete, so that you reachfar right to clip Bolt 3. Grab the juggy undercling block far left.
content.location: Far left of wall, after Snuff the Rooster

content.description: Anchors are over the left part of the high mini-roof.  Bolt 2 is right of the other bolts.  Ledge to start.
content.location: To the right of the hackberry tree.  To the right of Snuff the Rooster.

content.description: Rightmost route in the white limestone. Execute a crimpy boulder problem culminating in a jug sidepull. Finish on jugs.

Just left of the mini dihedral, starts on the mini arete formed by the bulge and the dihedral and then moves left up and over the bulge. 

  Pull hard moves on sharp pockets. 13a is the 21st century grade. 12d shouldn't be harder than half the 13a's in the park.

This wall is an arbitrary division of the Sex Canyon.  The right boundary of the wall is defined by Rock Mound #2 and the rounded arete described under Sex Canyon.  The wall name comes from a Limestoner route list and derives from a pre-County ownership destruction of a bee hive, probably to make a route "go".
